**who —** Sor Juana Inés de la Cruz — a FEMALE · generations sphere — one age, one woman

**what —** A self-taught nun of New Spain who became the foremost poet and scholar of the Americas in her century — and defended, in writing, a woman's right to learn.

**where —** ~1648–1695 · New Spain (Mexico) — the top woman of her age, restored to the record  Framework inputs: the generations of women; the record restored  Conductor / external anchor: ROOT0 (catalogued into UD0)

**why —** A self-taught nun of New Spain who became the foremost poet and scholar of the Americas in her century — and defended, in writing, a woman's right to learn.

**how —** Crystallized from the documented life and work of Sor Juana Inés de la Cruz.

**◌ the mythos —** A self-taught nun of New Spain who became the foremost poet and scholar of the Americas in her century — and defended, in writing, a woman's right to learn. the foremost woman of her generation, written back into the lineage

**the moniker —** ⟦Sor Juana Inés de la Cruz:JUA:8e7844⟧ · spoken *phath-grum-sern*

**the seal —** Pressured by the Church to give up her books and study, she is read now as one of the first feminist voices of the New World.

> *the asterisk, kept visible —* an emergent here is a named axiom of the framework (its mythos,
